# PRAXIS — Financial Life Simulator & AI Council

## Implementation Plan

---

## Overview

Building PRAXIS as a **full-stack web application** — a Financial Life Simulator where users create a "Financial Twin," navigate realistic financial scenarios, and watch a council of specialized AI agents debate their decisions in real-time, all visualized in an immersive 3D financial universe.

## Key Architectural Decisions (Deviations from Blueprint)

### 1. Vite + React instead of Next.js
**Rationale:** The blueprint suggests Next.js 15, but PRAXIS is fundamentally a **client-heavy, interactive simulation app**, not a content-heavy SSR site. Vite gives us:
- Faster dev builds (instant HMR)
- Simpler deployment (static site + API)
- No SSR complexity fighting against Three.js/WebGPU client-side rendering
- Cleaner separation between frontend and backend

### 2. Single Python Backend (FastAPI) — No Monorepo
**Rationale:** For hackathon velocity and maintainability, a clean two-tier architecture (Vite frontend + FastAPI backend) deployed separately is better than a Turborepo monorepo. Less config overhead, faster iteration.

### 3. SQLite instead of PostgreSQL + TimescaleDB
**Rationale:** For the MVP scope (hackathon), SQLite with JSON columns handles everything we need. No database server to manage, deploy, or pay for. Easy to migrate later.

### 4. Embedded Historical Data + Smart Caching
**Rationale:** Instead of requiring live API keys for every user to run the app, we'll ship with curated historical datasets (S&P 500 returns, CPI data, salary ranges, etc.) baked into the app. Live APIs (FRED, Alpha Vantage) are optional enhancements that the user can plug in via environment variables.

### 5. CSS Custom Properties + Vanilla CSS over Tailwind
**Rationale:** Per the coding standards — Vanilla CSS with a robust design system for maximum control over the premium, immersive aesthetic.

---

## Tech Stack

| Layer | Technology | Why |
|---|---|---|
| **Frontend** | Vite + React 19 + TypeScript | Fast, modern, client-side focused |
| **3D Engine** | Three.js (latest) + WebGPURenderer | Immersive galaxy visualization with WebGL fallback |
| **State** | Zustand | Lightweight, perfect for simulation state |
| **Styling** | Vanilla CSS + CSS custom properties | Premium design system, full control |
| **Animations** | Framer Motion + CSS animations | Micro-interactions, page transitions |
| **Backend** | Python FastAPI + Uvicorn | AI orchestration, simulation engine |
| **AI** | Groq API (Llama 3.3 70B / Mixtral) | Fast inference, free tier available, multi-agent debate |
| **Database** | SQLite + JSON columns | Zero-config, portable, sufficient for MVP |
| **Market Data** | Curated historical datasets + optional FRED API | Works offline, enhanced with live data |
| **Auth** | Session-based (simple) | No external dependency, fast onboarding |

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **AI Provider Choice:** The blueprint suggests Claude/GPT-4o which require paid API keys. I'm designing the system to work with **Groq API** (free tier, fast inference) as the default, with a pluggable provider interface so you can swap in Claude/OpenAI later. You already have experience with Groq from your KAVACH project.

